Below are 12 dictionary-style definitions of common English words. The headword
being defined has been removed from each entry, so you see only the definition
text. Read them as a lexicographer would and assess how natural they are as
human-authored dictionary entries -- the kind you would find in a general
dictionary such as Merriam-Webster, the Oxford Dictionary of English, or Collins.

Please answer, concretely and with quoted evidence:

(a) OVERALL NATURALNESS. On a 1-10 scale (10 = indistinguishable from a
    professionally edited general dictionary; 1 = obviously artificial), how
    natural do these read as human-authored dictionary entries? Give one number
    and justify it.

(b) STRUCTURAL TELLS. Is there a mechanical, formulaic, or repetitive SENTENCE-
    STRUCTURE pattern running through them -- something that would tell you the
    entries follow a rigid template or were machine-generated, rather than the
    varied prose an editorial team produces? Name the specific structural
    patterns you notice (clause shape, punctuation rhythm, opening constructions,
    the way second and third clauses are appended, recurring phrase frames, etc.)
    and QUOTE concrete examples from the entries for each pattern you name.

(c) WORST AND BEST. Which specific entries read as the LEAST natural / most
    templated, and which read as the MOST natural? Quote them and say why.

(d) DISCRIMINABILITY. Could a fluent English reader reliably distinguish this set
    from a real published dictionary on the basis of sentence STRUCTURE alone
    (setting aside the actual definitional content / word choice)? Roughly what
    accuracy would you expect such a reader to achieve, and on what structural
    cue would they most rely?

Be candid and specific; do not soften the assessment. Quote liberally.

--- THE DEFINITIONS ---

1. a spherical or rounded body used in games and sports; a toy of this form, thrown, struck, kicked, or rolled in play; any object whose surface is everywhere equally distant from its center, or nearly so, especially one made to bounce
2. to come into existence or operation; to take the first step of a process or action; to have a starting point in time
3. a stored reference that records the address of a document or web page so that the material may be reached again directly; an entry saved under a short descriptive title, allowing previously visited material to be retrieved without renewed searching
4. deprived of life; having permanently ceased all vital functions; no longer capable of action, sensation, or awareness
5. a domesticated carnivorous mammal closely related to the wolves, having a keen sense of smell and a barking voice, and bred from ancient times in a great variety of forms; kept as a companion, a guard, or a working animal
6. a male parent; a man who has begotten a child or who stands in a paternal relation toward one; the man responsible, together with the mother, for the upbringing and care of a child
7. an embrace in which one clasps another person closely in the arms, typically as an expression of affection, comfort, or greeting; a squeeze given with the arms about the body, often accompanying a welcome, a farewell, or congratulation
8. to bring into existence by shaping, constructing, or combining materials; to produce or fashion by deliberate work
9. the natural periodic state of rest during which the eyes are closed, the muscles are relaxed, consciousness is suspended, and the activity of the nervous system is diminished; a recurring condition of body and mind in which awareness of the surroundings ceases and the strength of the body is restored
10. capable of being seen; perceptible by the eye; open to view rather than hidden or obscured
11. an adult female human being; a female person who has attained full growth and maturity, as distinguished from a girl; a member of the sex that can conceive and bear children
12. contrary to morality or to accepted standards of conduct; not fit to be done; deserving of blame or censure when performed

