### (a) Overall naturalness: 4/10

Individual phrases often sound dictionary-like, but the set as a whole does not resemble the work of a professionally edited general dictionary. It reads like definitions generated from a rigid paraphrase-expansion template.

The central problem is excessive restatement. Instead of separating genuinely different senses, the entries repeatedly define the same sense two or three times:

> “deprived of life; having permanently ceased all vital functions; no longer capable of action, sensation, or awareness”

Likewise:

> “capable of being seen; perceptible by the eye; open to view rather than hidden or obscured”

Each fragment is plausible by itself. In aggregate, however, they feel mechanically constructed: initial definition, formal paraphrase, then clarifying or contrastive paraphrase. Professional dictionaries certainly use semicolons and compressed fragments, but not with this degree of uniformity across unrelated words.

There are also moments of artificial over-explanation. For example, the definition of *father* progresses from “a male parent” to “a man who has begotten a child” and then to:

> “the man responsible, together with the mother, for the upbringing and care of a child”

That sounds like an attempt to generate a third elaboration, not an independently edited dictionary sense.

### (b) Structural tells

The strongest tell is the nearly universal semicolon template. Every entry has one of these shapes:

> A; B  
> A; B; C

That is strikingly uniform across nouns, verbs, and adjectives. Examples include:

> “to come into existence or operation; to take the first step of a process or action; to have a starting point in time”

> “an adult female human being; a female person who has attained full growth and maturity, as distinguished from a girl; a member of the sex that can conceive and bear children”

> “contrary to morality or to accepted standards of conduct; not fit to be done; deserving of blame or censure when performed”

Several more specific patterns recur.

1. **Three successive paraphrases of one sense**

The semicolons generally do not introduce distinct meanings. They introduce successively expanded restatements:

> “deprived of life”  
> “having permanently ceased all vital functions”  
> “no longer capable of action, sensation, or awareness”

The same pattern occurs in:

> “capable of being seen; perceptible by the eye; open to view rather than hidden or obscured”

This “short gloss → formal reformulation → explanatory contrast” rhythm is highly mechanical.

2. **Identical grammatical openings after each semicolon**

The verb entries repeat infinitival clauses:

> “to come …; to take …; to have …”

The adjective entries use three parallel predicative fragments:

> “contrary to …; not fit …; deserving of …”

> “capable of …; perceptible by …; open to …”

The noun entries repeatedly restart with another article phrase:

> “a male parent; a man who …; the man responsible …”

> “an adult female human being; a female person who …; a member of the sex that …”

Parallelism can be elegant, but its systematic use here looks generated.

3. **Second-clause “definition of the definition”**

Many two-part entries state a definition and then manufacture a longer alternative version:

> “an embrace in which one clasps another person closely in the arms …; a squeeze given with the arms about the body …”

> “the natural periodic state of rest during which …; a recurring condition of body and mind in which …”

> “a stored reference that records the address …; an entry saved under a short descriptive title …”

These pairs do not supply clearly different senses. They are near-duplicate descriptions with changed wording.

4. **Recurring appended participial clauses**

Long entries often acquire extra information through comma-plus-participle constructions:

> “an entry saved under a short descriptive title, **allowing** previously visited material to be retrieved”

> “the wolves, **having** a keen sense of smell … and **bred** from ancient times”

> “a squeeze given with the arms about the body, **often accompanying** a welcome”

These additions create a recognizable generated cadence: main noun phrase, comma, participial elaboration.

5. **Predictable “typically/often/especially” modifiers**

The entries repeatedly soften or extend their final portions with adverbial qualifiers:

> “**especially** one made to bounce”

> “**typically** as an expression of affection”

> “**often** accompanying a welcome”

This is normal dictionary language individually, but here it forms part of the same expansion mechanism.

6. **Lack of normal editorial differentiation**

A real dictionary would likely handle some of these with numbered senses, usage labels, shorter wording, or carefully selected subsenses. Here everything is flattened into one flowing semicolon chain. The definition of *ball*, for example, joins a sporting object, a toy, and a geometric object in one uninterrupted triplet:

> “a spherical or rounded body used in games and sports; a toy of this form …; any object whose surface is everywhere equally distant from its center”

Structurally, that looks less like edited sense division than like three prompted elaborations concatenated together.

### (c) Worst and best

The least natural is entry 3:

> “a stored reference that records the address of a document or web page so that the material may be reached again directly; an entry saved under a short descriptive title, allowing previously visited material to be retrieved without renewed searching”

It is one long definition followed by another long definition of exactly the same thing. Both halves use the same conceptual sequence—saved reference, web material, later retrieval—but paraphrase each other laboriously. Phrases such as “without renewed searching” sound written to complete a formal-looking sentence rather than chosen for lexicographic economy.

Entry 6 is also conspicuously templated:

> “a male parent; a man who has begotten a child or who stands in a paternal relation toward one; the man responsible, together with the mother, for the upbringing and care of a child”

Its progression from “a male parent” to “a man” to “the man” is almost visibly algorithmic. The third clause is also not coextensive with the headword: not every father has responsibility for a child’s upbringing, and not every paternal caregiver is “the man” jointly responsible with the mother.

Entry 7 has the clearest redundant two-clause mirror:

> “an embrace in which one clasps another person closely in the arms …; a squeeze given with the arms about the body …”

“An embrace” and “a squeeze” are simply alternate hypernyms, while “closely in the arms” reappears as “with the arms about the body.”

The most natural is entry 8:

> “to bring into existence by shaping, constructing, or combining materials; to produce or fashion by deliberate work”

It is concise, grammatically clean, and its second clause could plausibly represent a slight broadening rather than pure padding. The two-part structure is still formulaic, but it is credible dictionary prose.

Entry 4 is also relatively natural:

> “deprived of life; having permanently ceased all vital functions; no longer capable of action, sensation, or awareness”

Its wording is economical and the fragments are well balanced. Its weakness emerges mainly in comparison with the rest of the set: it uses the same three-stage paraphrase template.

### (d) Discriminability

Yes. Given the entire set, a fluent reader could probably distinguish it from a comparable set of published dictionary entries with roughly **85% accuracy on structure alone**.

The decisive cue would be the repeated semicolon rhythm:

> short gloss; expanded restatement; final explanatory or contrastive restatement

A single entry such as “to bring into existence …; to produce or fashion …” could easily pass. Twelve consecutive entries built almost exclusively as `A; B` or `A; B; C`, with each unit paraphrasing the preceding one, are much harder to mistake for independently edited material.

The reader would rely less on any one awkward sentence than on the set-level regularity: identical punctuation, repeated grammatical resets, and the consistent pressure to supply a second and often a third formulation even when no separate sense exists. That regularity is the strongest evidence of templated or machine-generated construction.
